# Development Dockerfile with all tools
# Includes development dependencies and build tools
#
# Build: docker build -f Dockerfile.dev -t smrforge:dev .
# Or use: docker compose up smrforge-dev
#
# Last Updated: February 2026
# Recent Additions (February 2026):
# - Pro: Serpent import, MCNP converter, OpenMC tally viz, CLI convert/ml-export/report validation.
#   Pro workflows: nl-design, code-verify, regulatory-package, benchmark, multi-optimize. Build with -f Dockerfile.pro for Pro.
# - Dependency alignment: setup.py, requirements.txt, requirements-lock.txt consistent (httpx, tqdm).
# - Coding guidelines: optional deps fallbacks, Rich, convenience APIs, kwargs hygiene, path handling (docs/development/code-style.md).
# - Discovery and help: system_info(), help_topics(), list_constraint_sets(), get_example_path(), list_examples(), list_nuclides(), list_sweepable_params(); quick_optimize(), quick_uq(). See examples/discovery_help_example.py.
# - New convenience helpers: get_default_endf_dir(), list_endf_libraries(), list_geometry_types(), list_analysis_types(), list_surrogates(), quick_download_endf(). Also: quick_benchmark(), quick_safety_report(), quick_template_from_preset(), list_export_formats(), list_transient_types(), get_config(). Discovery: list_uq_sampling_methods(), list_optimization_objectives(), list_optimization_methods(), list_distributions(), list_economics_outputs(). Paths: get_default_config_path(), get_benchmark_path(). I/O: list_templates(), quick_export().
# - Rich display: system_info(display=True), quick_*(display=True); ENDF setup wizard uses Rich Panel/Table.
# - Convenience API consolidated: Legacy smrforge/convenience.py removed; all in smrforge/convenience/ package. No API changes.
# - Stable API (smrforge.api), AI audit (smrforge.ai), ML export (export_ml_dataset)
# - Serpent round-trip (Community): run_serpent, parse_res_file, run_and_parse in smrforge.io.serpent_run.
# - OpenMC integration (Community): Full export/import, subprocess runner, statepoint HDF5 parsing. See examples/openmc_export_example.py.
# - Rich colorized logging: Console logging uses RichHandler for color-coded levels (DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL), rich tracebacks. File logging remains plain text. Set NO_COLOR=1 to disable colors.
# - Documentation: README and technical docs clarify SMRForge is original work; OpenMC/Serpent references are inspiration and analysis, not code derivation.
# Recent Additions (January 2026):
# - Pint mandatory: pint>=0.20.0 now in setup.py install_requires (required for unit checking)
# - Memory and performance profiling: profile_performance.py, run_performance_profile.*, update_performance_baselines.py, smrforge.utils.profiling. See docs/development/memory-and-performance-assessment.md.
# - Creep models (primary, secondary, tertiary, irradiation-enhanced) for fuel rod materials
# - Material degradation models for long-term fuel rod analysis
# - Multi-physics coupling framework (unified coupling of all physics domains)
# - Model Predictive Control (MPC) for advanced reactor control algorithms
# - Fuel Performance module (temperature calculations, swelling, fission gas release)
# - General Optimization module (design optimization, loading pattern optimization)
# - General I/O Utilities module (JSON/YAML/CSV readers/writers, format converters)
# Regulatory Traceability (Complete):
# - Calculation audit trails - Complete input → output traceability for licensing applications
# - Model assumption documentation - Explicit assumption tracking per calculation
# - Safety margin reports - Automated safety margin calculations with text/JSON export
# - BEPU methodology support - Best Estimate Plus Uncertainty workflow integration
# Phase 3 Optimizations (Complete):
# - Implicit Monte Carlo (IMC) for transients - 5-10x faster for time-dependent calculations
# - Enhanced memory pooling - 5-10% speedup, reduced allocation overhead
# - Memory-mapped files - Enable datasets larger than RAM
# Phase 2 Optimizations (Foundation Complete):
# - Adaptive sampling - 2-5x faster convergence by focusing on important regions
# - Hybrid solver - 10-100x faster than pure MC (diffusion + MC combination)
# Phase 1 Optimizations (Complete):
# - Progress indicators with Rich library
# - Enhanced error messages with suggestions
# - Code formatting (black, isort, mypy)
# - Parallel batch processing
# - Enhanced vectorization
# - JIT optimization (fastmath, nogil, boundscheck=False) - 90-95% of C++ performance
# - Added comprehensive CLI with nested subcommands (reactor, data, burnup, validate, visualize, config, shell, workflow)
# - Added batch processing support for reactor analysis
# - Added interactive shell mode (IPython/REPL) via `smrforge shell`
# - Added workflow scripts support (YAML-based workflows) via `smrforge workflow run`
# - Added configuration management (`smrforge config show/set/init`)
# - Added validation testing framework with benchmark comparison
# - Added tab completion scripts (Bash/Zsh and PowerShell)
# - Enhanced CLI with Rich library (colored output, tables, progress bars)
# - Added Parameter Sweep Workflow (smrforge sweep) - automated parameter sweeps with parallel execution
# - Enhanced Design Comparison & Trade Studies (smrforge reactor compare) - multi-design comparison with metrics
# - Added Template Library System (smrforge reactor template) - parameterized reactor design templates
# - Added Simulation Checkpointing & Resume - automatic checkpointing for long burnup simulations
# - Added Design Constraints & Validation (smrforge validate design) - automated constraint checking
# - Added I/O Converters Framework - Serpent/OpenMC format support (framework ready)
# - Added Dash web dashboard with dark/gray mode support
# - Added CLI command (smrforge serve) for dashboard
# - Added Geometry Designer GUI - Interactive visual core layout editor with material palette, 3D preview, export/import
# - Added LWR SMR transient analysis (PWR/BWR/Integral SMR transients)
# - Added LWR SMR burnup features (gadolinium depletion, assembly/rod-wise tracking)
# - Added automated data downloader with parallel downloads (tqdm, pyyaml)
# - Added Pint-based unit checking (pint>=0.20.0)
# - Added lumped-parameter thermal hydraulics (fast 0-D thermal circuits)
# - Added simplified point kinetics API (quick transient analysis)
# - Added transient and thermal visualization capabilities
# - Updated dashboard with quick transient and lumped thermal analysis interfaces
# - Optimized Monte Carlo solver (5-10x faster, 50-70% memory reduction)
#   * Vectorized particle tracking with NumPy arrays (ParticleBank class)
#   * Memory pooling for reduced allocations
#   * Parallel processing with Numba prange (scales with CPU cores)
#   * Pre-computed cross-section lookup tables (faster XS access)
#   * Batch tally processing (reduced overhead)
#   * Based on OpenMC's optimization strategies
# - Visualization dependencies (plotly, pyvista, dash) are now required and included automatically
# - Fixed Debian Trixie compatibility (libgl1 instead of libgl1-mesa-glx)
# - Fixed Dash 3.x API compatibility (app.run() instead of app.run_server())
# - Fixed dashboard preset loading and validation issues
# - Convenience API: create_reactor, list_presets from smrforge.convenience package (consolidated Feb 2026)
# - Fixed dashboard State component initialization (all analysis options always in layout)
# - Fixed LumpedThermalHydraulics parameter passing (adaptive/max_step moved to solve_transient)
# - Improved validation warning messages (show actual validation details)
# - Comprehensive CLI guide documentation (docs/guides/cli-guide.md)
# - Updated tutorial with CLI usage and advanced features (docs/guides/tutorial.md)
# - Help system integration (smr.help() function for interactive documentation)
# - Complete dashboard workflow: reactor creation → analysis → results → export
# - Real data capture: flux and power distributions from solver
# - Enhanced visualizations: plots use actual solver data, not sample data
# - Complete exports: JSON/CSV include reactor spec + analysis results
# - Project save/open: full workflow persistence with data restoration
# - Enhanced error handling and user feedback throughout dashboard
# - Added pytest-asyncio for async test support
# - Added system libraries for 3D visualization
# - Optional: mesh conversion (meshio) and CAD import (trimesh) dependencies
# - Updated to support latest features and test requirements
# - Test coverage: 79.2% overall, 75-80%+ on priority modules (239+ new tests added in latest session)
# - Recent coverage improvements (January 19, 2026):
#   * core/multigroup_advanced.py: 35.7% → 76.4% (+35 tests, bug fix)
#   * validation/standards_parser.py: 44.0% → 93.5% (+32 tests)
#   * validation/regulatory_traceability.py: 0% → 100% (+46 tests)
#   * burnup/lwr_burnup.py: 47.2% → 100% (+33 tests)
#   * economics/integration.py: 0% → 100% (+11 tests)
# - CLI test coverage: 71.8% (130+ passing tests covering all major CLI commands and edge cases)
# - Comprehensive test suite: 194+ test files including Phase 1/2 module tests, __init__.py import error path tests, utility module tests, and CLI tests
# - Utility module coverage: memory_mapped.py (100%), parallel_batch.py (67.2%), error_messages.py (98.2%), optimization_utils.py (97.8%), memory_pool.py (100%), material_mapping.py (100%), units.py (improved), logo.py (improved), logging.py (improved)
# - Advanced error handling and async edge case coverage
# - New test files: test_parameter_sweep, test_templates, test_constraints, test_converters, test_burnup_checkpointing, test_memory_mapped, test_parallel_batch, test_error_messages, test_optimization_utils, test_memory_pool, test_material_mapping, test_burnup_init, test_validation_init, test_convenience_init, test_presets_init, test_version, test_utils_units, test_utils_error_messages, test_utils_logo, test_utils_logging, test_help, test_data_downloader
# - Advanced tests: test_reactor_core_advanced_error_handling, test_reactor_core_async_edge_cases
# - Manual testing framework: 13 test scripts (test_*.py) for feature validation (testing/ directory)
#   Optional Jupyter notebooks available for interactive testing (01_CLI_Commands.ipynb)
# - Quick start validation guide for running tests with real ENDF data (docs/validation/QUICK_START_VALIDATION.md)
# - API consistency improvements: Enhanced docstrings with unit documentation, dual API pattern examples
# - API Style Guide: Comprehensive guide for consistent API design (docs/guides/API_STYLE_GUIDE.md)
# - API Consistency Report: Detailed analysis of API patterns (docs/status/API_CONSISTENCY_REPORT.md)

FROM python:3.11-slim

# Metadata labels
LABEL maintainer="SMRForge Development Team" \
      description="SMRForge Development Environment" \
      version="0.1.0-dev" \
      org.opencontainers.image.title="SMRForge Community (Dev)" \
      org.opencontainers.image.description="SMRForge Community Edition - development environment"

WORKDIR /app

# Headless-friendly defaults for containers:
# - MPLBACKEND=Agg avoids GUI backends in headless environments
# - PYVISTA_OFF_SCREEN=true helps avoid display requirements
ENV PYTHONUNBUFFERED=1 \
    PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 \
    PIP_NO_CACHE_DIR=1 \
    MPLBACKEND=Agg \
    PYVISTA_OFF_SCREEN=true \
    SMRFORGE_TIER=community

# Install system dependencies including development tools
# Added libgl1 and libglib2.0-0 for pyvista visualization support
ENV DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive
RUN apt-get update && \
    apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    build-essential \
    gfortran \
    cmake \
    pkg-config \
    libhdf5-dev \
    libblas-dev \
    liblapack-dev \
    libxml2-dev \
    libpng-dev \
    libgl1 \
    libglib2.0-0 \
    libxrender1 \
    libfontconfig1 \
    libgomp1 \
    libffi-dev \
    git \
    vim \
    curl \
    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

# Copy dependency manifests first (better layer caching)
COPY requirements.txt requirements-lock.txt requirements-dev.txt /app/

# Copy package metadata first (for better layer caching)
COPY setup.py pyproject.toml README.md README_PYPI.md MANIFEST.in /app/
COPY smrforge/ /app/smrforge/
# Copy CLI scripts and utilities (validation scripts, completion scripts, etc.)
COPY scripts/ /app/scripts/

# Copy testing infrastructure (manual test scripts and documentation)
COPY testing/ /app/testing/
COPY docs/testing/ /app/docs/testing/
# Copy main test suite and examples (for standalone dev builds; docker-compose mounts over these)
COPY examples/ /app/examples/
COPY tests/ /app/tests/

# Install Python dependencies
RUN pip install --upgrade pip wheel setuptools

# Install dev dependencies (includes core deps via -r requirements.txt)
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r /app/requirements-dev.txt

# Install SMRForge (editable for development workflows)
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -e .

# Optional: Install additional mesh conversion and CAD import dependencies
# Uncomment the next lines to include mesh conversion and CAD import support:
# RUN pip install --no-cache-dir \
#     meshio>=5.0.0 \
#     trimesh>=3.0.0
# Note: joblib is already included as a dependency of scikit-learn

# Create directories for data/output/results and ENDF storage
# ENDF data can be mounted as volume or stored in container
RUN mkdir -p /app/data /app/output /app/results /app/endf-data

# Set environment variable for standard ENDF directory
# Users can override this or mount their own ENDF directory
# Also supports configuration file: ~/.smrforge/config.yaml
ENV SMRFORGE_ENDF_DIR=/app/endf-data

# Common ports:
# - 8050: Dash dashboard (`smrforge serve`)
# - 8888: Jupyter (optional)
EXPOSE 8050 8888

# Default to bash shell for interactive development
# Note: ENDF files can be downloaded automatically using the data downloader
# Run: smrforge data download --library ENDF-B-VIII.1 --output /app/endf-data
# Or: python -c "from smrforge.data_downloader import download_endf_data; download_endf_data(library='ENDF/B-VIII.1', output_dir='/app/endf-data')"
# Or set up manually: smrforge data setup
# 
# To run the web dashboard:
#   smrforge serve --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8050
#   Or: python -c "from smrforge.gui import run_server; run_server(host='0.0.0.0', port=8050)"
#   Then access at http://localhost:8050 (map port 8050 in docker compose)
#
# CLI Commands available:
#   smrforge reactor create/list/analyze/compare
#   smrforge reactor template create/modify/validate (template library)
#   smrforge data setup/download/validate
#   smrforge burnup run/visualize (with checkpointing support)
#   smrforge transient run (quick transient analysis - reactivity insertion, decay heat, etc.)
#   smrforge thermal lumped (lumped-parameter thermal hydraulics)
#   smrforge validate run (validation framework - run validation tests)
#   smrforge validate design (design constraints validation)
#   smrforge visualize geometry/flux
#   smrforge config show/set/init
#   smrforge shell (interactive IPython/REPL)
#   smrforge workflow run (YAML workflows)
#   smrforge sweep (parameter sweep and sensitivity analysis)
#   All new modules available via Python imports:
#     - smrforge.mechanics (FuelRodMechanics, ThermalExpansion, StressStrain, PCI, FuelSwelling)
#     - smrforge.control (PIDController, ReactorController, LoadFollowingController, ModelPredictiveController)
#     - smrforge.economics (CapitalCostEstimator, OperatingCostEstimator, LCOECalculator)
#     - smrforge.fuel_cycle (FuelCycleOptimizer, RefuelingStrategyOptimizer, MaterialAging)
#     - smrforge.fuel (FuelPerformance, FuelProperties, CladProperties)
#     - smrforge.optimization (DesignOptimizer, LoadingPatternOptimizer, OptimizationResult)
#     - smrforge.io (InputReader, OutputWriter, SerpentConverter, OpenMCConverter)
#     - smrforge.thermal.two_phase_advanced (DriftFluxModel, TwoFluidModel, BoilingHeatTransfer)
#
# Development Features:
#   - Web Dashboard (smrforge serve) with dark/gray mode
#   - Comprehensive CLI with nested subcommands
#   - Interactive shell (smrforge shell)
#   - Workflow scripts (smrforge workflow run)
#   - Batch processing support
#   - Parameter Sweep Workflow (smrforge sweep)
#   - Enhanced Design Comparison (smrforge reactor compare)
#   - Template Library System (smrforge reactor template)
#   - Simulation Checkpointing & Resume
#   - Design Constraints & Validation (smrforge validate design)
#   - I/O Converters Framework (Serpent/OpenMC)
#   - Validation framework with benchmark comparison
#   - LWR SMR transient analysis (PWR/BWR/Integral SMR)
#   - LWR SMR burnup features (gadolinium depletion, assembly/rod tracking)
#   - Quick transient analysis (reactivity insertion, decay heat removal)
#   - Lumped-parameter thermal hydraulics (fast 0-D thermal circuits)
#   - Pint-based unit checking and dimensional analysis
#   - Transient and thermal visualization
#   - Optimized Monte Carlo solver (5-10x faster than original)
#     * Vectorized particle tracking
#     * Parallel processing with Numba
#     * Memory pooling (50-70% reduction)
#   - Structural mechanics module (fuel rod mechanics, stress/strain, PCI, fuel swelling, creep models, material degradation)
#   - Advanced control systems (PID controllers, load-following, reactor control, Model Predictive Control)
#   - Economics cost modeling (capital costs, operating costs, LCOE calculations with SMR-specific factors)
#   - Regulatory traceability: Calculation audit trails, assumption documentation, safety margin reports, BEPU support
#   - Advanced two-phase flow models:
#     * Drift-flux models (Zuber-Findlay, Chexal-Lellouche, Ishii-Mishima)
#     * Two-fluid models for detailed analysis
#     * Enhanced boiling heat transfer correlations (Chen, Forster-Zuber, Gorenflo)
#     * Critical Heat Flux (CHF) predictions (Bowring, Biasi, Groeneveld)
#   - Fuel cycle optimization and long-term simulation:
#     * Fuel cycle optimization algorithms (cycle length, enrichment, multi-objective)
#     * Refueling strategy optimization (batch configuration, frequency)
#     * Material aging models (graphite, zircaloy, fuel)
#     * Enhanced thermal-hydraulics coupling for long transients
#   - Parallel multi-group diffusion solver:
#     * Parallel energy group solve with red-black ordering (ThreadPoolExecutor)
#     * Parallel spatial operations with Numba prange
#     * Parallel scattering source updates
#     * Expected 4-8x speedup on multi-core CPUs
#   - MPI support (optional):
#     * Distributed memory support via mpi4py
#     * Helper functions for MPI rank, size, root detection
#     * Graceful fallback if MPI not available
#   - Comprehensive CLI guide (docs/guides/cli-guide.md):
#     * Complete documentation of all CLI commands and subcommands
#     * Examples and usage patterns for all features
#     * Troubleshooting guide and command quick reference
#   - Regulatory traceability guide (docs/technical/regulatory-traceability-guide.md):
#     * Complete guide for licensing applications and regulatory compliance
#     * Audit trail usage, assumption documentation, safety margin reports, BEPU methodology
#   - Robust CLI import handling:
#     * Multiple import strategies for convenience functions
#     * Handles module/package conflicts gracefully
#   - Automated ENDF data downloader
#   - Advanced visualization, geometry import (OpenMC/Serpent/CAD/MCNP)
#   - Enhanced mesh generation
#   - Geometry Designer GUI - Interactive visual core layout editor
#   - Advanced optimization algorithms (GA, PSO) for fuel cycle optimization
#   - Fuel Performance module (fuel temperature, swelling, fission gas release)
#   - General Optimization module (reactor design optimization, loading pattern optimization)
#   - General I/O Utilities (file readers/writers, format converters for Serpent/OpenMC)
#   - Advanced interfacial transfer models for two-phase flow
#   - Comprehensive test suite (5001 tests, 44 skipped; pytest --ignore tests/test_smrforge_pro)
#     * Phase 1/2 module tests: parameter_sweep, templates, constraints, converters, checkpointing
#     * Utility module tests: memory_mapped (100%), parallel_batch (67.2%), error_messages (98.2%), optimization_utils (97.8%), memory_pool (100%), material_mapping (100%), units (improved), logo (improved), logging (improved)
#     * __init__.py import error path tests: burnup, validation, convenience, presets
#     * CLI module tests: 71.8% coverage (130+ passing tests covering all major CLI commands, edge cases, error handling)
#     * Advanced error handling tests: file operations, copy failures, validation errors
#     * Async edge case tests: partial failures, exception propagation, timeouts, concurrent access
#   - Manual testing framework: 13 test scripts for feature validation
#
# Running Automated Tests:
#   pytest  # Run all automated tests
#   pytest tests/performance/... --run-performance -v --override-ini "addopts=-v --strict-markers --tb=short -ra"  # Performance benchmarks (time + memory)
#   pytest tests/test_parameter_sweep.py -v  # Test parameter sweep workflow
#   pytest tests/test_templates.py -v  # Test template library
#   pytest tests/test_constraints.py -v  # Test design constraints
#   pytest tests/test_burnup_checkpointing.py -v  # Test checkpointing
#   pytest tests/test_reactor_core_advanced_error_handling.py -v  # Test error handling
#   pytest tests/test_reactor_core_async_edge_cases.py -v  # Test async operations
#   pytest --cov=smrforge --cov-report=html:coverage/generated/htmlcov  # Coverage report
#
# Running performance profiling (see docs/development/memory-and-performance-assessment.md):
#   python scripts/profile_performance.py --function keff --mode both
#   ./scripts/run_performance_profile.sh  # Linux/macOS; use run_performance_profile.ps1 on Windows
#   python scripts/update_performance_baselines.py  # Suggest BASELINE_* updates
#
# Running Manual Tests:
#   # First, generate test data files (required for some tests):
#   python testing/generate_test_data.py  # Generate burnup, flux, sweep, and checkpoint data
#   # This creates:
#   #   - testing/test_data/burnup_results.json
#   #   - testing/test_data/flux_results.json
#   #   - testing/test_data/sweep_results.json
#   #   - testing/test_data/checkpoints/checkpoint_5.0.h5  (if h5py is available)
#   #   - (plots/HTML outputs go under testing/results/)
#   
#   python testing/test_01_cli_commands.py  # Test CLI commands
#   python testing/test_02_reactor_creation.py  # Test reactor creation/analysis
#   python testing/test_03_burnup.py  # Test burnup calculations (uses testing/test_data/burnup_results.json)
#   python testing/test_04_parameter_sweep.py  # Test parameter sweep (uses testing/test_data/sweep_results.json)
#   python testing/test_05_templates.py  # Test template library
#   python testing/test_06_constraints.py  # Test design constraints
#   python testing/test_07_io_converters.py  # Test I/O converters
#   python testing/test_08_data_management.py  # Test data management
#   python testing/test_09_validation.py  # Test validation framework
#   python testing/test_10_visualization.py  # Test visualization (uses testing/test_data/burnup_results.json and flux_results.json)
#   python testing/test_11_workflows.py  # Test workflow scripts
#   python testing/test_12_config.py  # Test configuration
#   python testing/test_13_advanced.py  # Test advanced features
#   # Optional Jupyter notebooks: testing/01_CLI_Commands.ipynb (example for interactive testing)
#   # Notebooks are optional - Python scripts (test_*.py) are the primary testing method
#   # See docs/testing/MANUAL_TESTING_CHECKLIST.md for complete guide
#   # See docs/validation/QUICK_START_VALIDATION.md for ENDF validation testing
#
# API Documentation:
#   - API Style Guide: docs/guides/API_STYLE_GUIDE.md (comprehensive API design guidelines)
#   - API Consistency Report: docs/status/API_CONSISTENCY_REPORT.md (detailed API analysis)
#   - All functions document units clearly (power_mw -> watts, time_steps -> days)
#   - Dual API patterns documented (visualization, nuclear data access)
CMD ["/bin/bash"]

